mily_orbit","related_id":"X02067","display_label":"His wife Anna Sinton's father David Sinton left her $20 million — Ohio's largest fortune in 1900. Sinton money financed the presidential bid.","link_text":"David Sinton"}],"notable":{"is_notable":true,"notable_category":["politics","business","journalism"],"notable_blurb":"Owned the Chicago Cubs and Philadelphia Phillies","primary_url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Charles_Phelps_Taft","primary_url_label":"Wikipedia"},"narrative_blocks":[{"header":"He owned the Cubs and the Phillies","body":"Charles Phelps Taft became a minority owner of the Chicago Cubs in 1905 and helped fund the purchase of the Philadelphia Phillies in 1909 — publicly denying the connection until it became untenable. After serving one term as a congressman and building the Cincinnati Times-Star into the foundation of a media empire, his greatest business legacy was baseball. He sold the Cubs after the 1915 season and his estate, the Taft Museum of Art, is now open to the public.","number":1},{"header":"His half-brother accepted the presidential nomination","body":"William Howard Taft accepted the 1908 Republican presidential nomination standing on the portico of Charles Phelps Taft's Cincinnati home at 316 Pike Street — the house their father-in-law David Sinton had purchased and that Charles and Anna later bequeathed to the public as the Taft Museum of Art. The nomination scene on that portico is one of the moments that cement the house's place in American political history.","number":2}],"bio":{"display_name":"Charles Phelps Taft","first_name":"Charles","last_name":"Taft","married_names":[],"middle_name":"Phelps","photo_url":"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/a5/Taft_5579668698_7d2741cb4a_o.jpg/500px-Taft_5579668698_7d2741cb4a_o.jpg"},"residence":{},"baptism":{},"research_tags":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"artworks":[],"quotes":[],"military_service":[],"slug":"charles-taft-1843"},"X02068